Infrainguinal reconstruction with arm vein, lesser saphenous vein, and remnants 
of greater saphenous vein: a report of 257 cases.

Londrey GL(1), Bosher LP, Brown PW, Stoneburner FD Jr, Pancoast JW, Davis RK.

Author information:
(1)Virginia Surgical Associates, P.C., Richmond 23226.

PURPOSE: The purpose of this study was to evaluate the results of infrainguinal 
reconstructions with arm vein, lesser saphenous vein, and remnants of greater 
saphenous vein (ectopic vein grafts).
METHODS: The records of 222 patients who underwent 257 bypasses were 
restrospectively reviewed. Most of the grafts were placed for rest pain or 
tissue loss (88%) and were secondary reconstructions (70%) to the infrapopliteal 
level (90%). Single-length vein grafts were constructed in 66% of cases, whereas 
34% were composite vein grafts.
